# Design heuristics

Path-scoped rule. Loads on UI work, alongside `.claude/rules/design-system.md`. The project-specific applications of established UX laws — the ratios and limits this product has chosen, plus its specific ARIA targets. Where the design system rule is silent on a specific case, these heuristics decide it.

## 1. Hick's law — action ceiling

_Hick 1952: more options = more decision time._

**Rule:** No primary surface exposes more than <!-- PARAMETERIZE: action_ceiling_count --> primary actions simultaneously. Secondary actions go behind a menu or appear on hover. Adding a fourth visible action: stop.

## 2. Fitts's law — target size and adjacency

_Fitts 1954: acquisition time depends on distance and target size._

**Rule:** Minimum interactive target size is 44×44px — icon-only buttons, nav items, chip toggles. Never place two destructive targets adjacent with less than `--space-3` between them.

## 3. Miller's law — content blocks per card

_Miller 1956: working memory holds ~7±2 chunks._

**Rule:** <!-- PARAMETERIZE: miller_application -->.

## 4. Nielsen — visibility of system status

**Rule:** Every surface communicates what is happening. Loading, error, empty, and success states are all defined for every data surface. No surface renders silently empty or silently broken. Status communicated through content and iconography, not color alone.

## 5. Nielsen — error prevention over recovery

**Rule:** Prevent errors before they happen. When an error does occur, explain how to fix it, not just what went wrong. Required fields are obvious. Selection rules ("choose one" / "choose all that apply") are always visible.

## 6. ARIA targets

<!-- PARAMETERIZE: aria_specific_rules -->

Icon-only buttons require `aria-label`. `title` alone is not sufficient. It announces inconsistently across screen readers and not at all on mobile. No exceptions.

